08656nam a22010575i 9780812290318DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979756717  a97808122903187 a10.9783/97808122903182doi  a(DE-B1597)451239  a(OCoLC)897176580  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aSOC0020002bisacsh00aMutuality :bAnthropology's Changing Terms of Engagement /ced. by Roger Sanjek. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2014] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b16 illus  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Deep Grooves: Anthropology and Mutuality -- tPart I. Orientations -- tChapter 1. Anthropology and the American Indian -- tChapter 2. The American Anthropological Association RACE: Are We So Different? Project -- tChapter 3. Mutuality and the Field at Home -- tChapter 4. “If You Want to Go Fast, Go Alone. If You Want to Go Far, Go Together”: Yup’ik Elders Working Together with One Mind -- tPart II. Roots -- tChapter 5. The Invisibility of Diasporic Capital and Multiply Migrant Creativity -- tChapter 6. A Savage at the Wedding and the Skeletons in My Closet: My Great-Grandfather, “Igorotte Villages,” and the Ethnological Expositions of the 1900s -- tChapter 7. Thinking About and Experiencing Mutuality: Notes on a Son’s Formation -- tChapter 8. Cartographies of Mutuality: Lessons from Darfur -- tPart III. Journeys -- tChapter 9. On the Fault Lines of the Discipline: Personal Practice and the Canon -- tChapter 10. Listening with Passion: A Journey Through Engagement and Exchange -- tChapter 11. Why? And How? An Essay on Doing Anthropology and Life -- tChapter 12. Embedded in Time, Work, Family, and Age: A Reverie About Mutuality -- tPart IV. Publics -- tChapter 13. Dancing in the Chair: A Collaborative Effort of Developing and Implementing Wheelchair Taijiquan -- tChapter 14. Fragments of a Limited Mutuality -- tChapter 15. On “Making Good” in a Study of African American Children with Acquired and Traumatic Brain Injuries -- tChapter 16. On Ethnographic Love -- tConclusion. Mutuality and Anthropology: Terms and Modes of Engagement -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tList of Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhy do people do social-cultural anthropology? Beyond professional career motivations, what values underpin anthropologists' commitments to lengthy training, fieldwork, writing, and publication? Mutuality explores the values that anthropologists bring from their wider social worlds, including the value placed on relationships with the people they study, work with, write about and for, and communicate with more broadly.In this volume, seventeen distinguished anthropologists draw on personal and professional histories to describe avenues to mutuality through collaborative fieldwork, community-based projects and consultations, advocacy, and museum exhibits, including the American Anthropological Association's largest public outreach ever—the RACE: Are We So Different? project. Looking critically at obstacles to reciprocally beneficial engagement, the contributors trace the discipline's past and current relations with Native Americans, indigenous peoples exhibited in early twentieth-century world's fairs, and racialized populations. The chapters range widely—across the Punjabi craft caste, Filipino Igorot, and Somali Bantu global diasporas; to the Darfur crisis and conciliation efforts in Sudan and Qatar; to applied work in Panama, Micronesia, China, and Peru. In the United States, contributors discuss their work as academic, practicing, and public anthropologists in such diverse contexts as Alaskan Yup'ik communities, multiethnic New Mexico, San Francisco's Japan Town, Oakland's Intertribal Friendship House, Southern California's produce markets, a children's ward in a Los Angeles hospital, a New England nursing home, and Washington D.C.'s National Mall. Deeply personal as well as professionally astute, Mutuality sheds new light on the issues closest to the present and future of contemporary anthropology.Contributors: Rogaia Mustafa Abusharaf, Robert R. Alvarez, Garrick Bailey, Catherine Besteman, Parminder Bhachu, Ann Fienup-Riordan, Zibin Guo, Lane Ryo Hirabayashi, Lanita Jacobs, Susan Lobo, Yolanda T. Moses, Sylvia Rodríguez, Roger Sanjek, Renée R. Shield, Alaka Wali, Deana L. Weibel, Brett Williams.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAnthropologyxFieldworkxMethodology. 0aAnthropologyxMethodology. 0aEthnologyxFieldworkxMethodology. 0aEthnologyxMethodology. 0aIch-Du-Beziehung. 0aInterpersonal relations. 0aJewish interpretations of Jesus Christ. 0aRelations humaines. 0aZwischenmenschliche Beziehung. 4aFolklore. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aFolklore.  aLinguistics.1 aAbusharaf, Rogaia Mustafa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlvarez, Robert R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBailey, Garrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBesteman, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhachu, Parminder, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFienup-Riordan, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuo, Zibin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirabayashi, Lane Ryo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobs, Lanita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLobo, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id